<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100437217612898></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100437217612898><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=2190&mid=100437217612898>Regarding Haste Percentages</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=2190&mid=100437217612898#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=43695><span id=Sage>Argfeld</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>52 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Oct 29th 11:16 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.70]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>There are two accepted ways to calculate haste percentage.&nbsp;&nbsp;If you use one of these two methods to calculate haste on "dragon haste" items, you will generally get 40% or 41%.  If you use the other method (on the exact same items), you will get about 35% or 36%.  This makes it a royal pain to figure out which of two haste items is better because you often have no idea which method was used to calculate the haste.  I can almost guarantee that if you see a haste item that drops off a dragon or some other truly uber creature like Dain Frostweaver or King Tormax or something inside Sleeper's Tomb, that it will have "dragon haste".<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
